<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="I"><UNDER>AMENDED</UNDER> NOTICE OF APPEAL</TI>
<P>THE DEFENDANTS <UNDER>2487048 ONTARIO LIMITED</UNDER>, MIKE ALLEN AND CLARK KENT APPEAL to the Court of Appeal from the Judgement of the Honourable Justice Boswell dated March 7<SUP>th</SUP>, 2018 made at Barrie.</P>
<P>THE APPELLANTS <UNDER>2487048 ONTARIO LIMITED</UNDER>, MIKE ALLEN AND CLARK KENT ASK that the Judgment be set aside and an Order be granted dismissing the Plaintiffs' motion for judgement with costs.</P>
<P>THE GROUNDS OF APPEAL are as follows:
<P1>a) The learned Motions Court Judge erred in piercing the corporate veil and affixing personal liability on the Appellants.</P1>
<P1>b) The learned Motions Court Judge erred in finding that the Appellants used 2487048 ONTARIO LIMITED to engage in improper and dishonest conduct.</P1>
<P1>c) The learned Motions Court Judge erred in finding that <UNDER>any of</UNDER> the Appellants <UNDER><STRIKE>or 2487048 ONTARIO LIMITED</STRIKE></UNDER> had converted the Plaintiffs' assets to themselves.</P1>
<P1>d) The learned Motions Court Judge erred in finding that the Appellants had attempted to use the corporate entity to commit dishonest or improper acts.</P1>
<P1>e) The learned Motions Court Judge erred in finding that improper acts on the part of a corporate entity are sufficient to affix personal liability on the corporate entity's directors and/or controlling minds.</P1>
<P1>f) The learned Motions Court Judge erred in finding that the Asset Purchase Agreement obliged 2487048 ONTARIO LIMITED to assume responsibility for the leasehold improvement loan.</P1>
<P1>g) The learned Motions Court Judge erred in finding, on the evidence, that the Appellants cheated the Plaintiffs out of the assets of the business.</P1>
<P1>h) The learned Motions Court Judge erred in finding that the Appellant 2487048 ONTARIO LIMITED was in breach of the Asset Purchase Agreement.</P1>
<P1>i) The learned Motions Court Judge erred in finding that the clawback of deferred rent was a foreseeable consequence of non-payment by the Appellant 2487048 ONTARIO LIMITED of amounts pursuant to the Asset Purchase Agreement.</P1>
<P1>j) The learned Motions Court Judge erred in his interpretation of the Asset Purchase Agreement.</P1>
<P1>k) There was absolutely no evidence upon which the learned Motions Court Judge could make a decision as to what was reasonably foreseeable with regard to payment of deferred rent.</P1>
<P1>l) There was absolutely no evidence upon which the learned Motions Court Judge could have made any finding as to what was in the contemplation of the Appellant 2487048 ONTARIO LIMITED with regard to the deferred rent.</P1>
<P1>m) The learned Motions Court Judge erred in finding that the Plaintiffs reasonably settled the landlord's claim.</P1>
<P1>n) The learned Motions Court Judge erred, by reversing the onus of proof, in allowing the Plaintiffs' claim for costs it paid the landlord on the basis that he did not have a sufficient evidentiary record to persuade him that the costs were unreasonable.</P1>
<P1>o) Such further and other grounds as counsel may advise and this Honourable Court may permit.</P1></P>
<P>THE BASIS OF THE APPELLATE COURT'S JURISDICTION IS:
<P1>a) The Judgment is a final order for payment of the sum of $58,697.06 <UNDER>by the Appellants Mike Allen and Clark Kent.</UNDER></P1>
<P1>b) <UNDER>The Judgment is a final order for payment of the sum of $85.637.97 by the Appellant 2487048 ONTARIO LIMITED.</UNDER></P1>
<P1>c) The <EM>Courts of Justice Act</EM> 6(1) gives the Court of Appeal jurisdiction over a final order of a judge in the Superior Court of Justice. 19(1)(a) does not apply as the judgment is in excess of $50,000.00.</P1>
<P1>d) Leave to appeal is not required.</P1></P>
<P><UNDER>May 15<SUP>th</SUP></UNDER>, 2018</P>
