<BLOCK1><TI>FACTUM OF THE APPELLANTS 2487048 ONTARIO LIMITED, MIKE ALLEN and CLARK KENT</TI>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="I">PART I&mdash;ORDERS APPEALED FROM</TI>
<P>1. This is an appeal by the Appellants, 2487048 ONTARIO LIMITED, MIKE ALLEN and CLARK KENT, from Orders of Justice Boswell dated November 27<SUP>th</SUP>, 2017 and March 7<SUP>th</SUP>, 2018 granting judgment in the amount of $85,637.97 against the Appellant 2487048 ONTARIO LIMITED and granting judgment in the amount of $58,697.06 against the Appellants MIKE ALLEN and CLARK KENT respectively.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="II">PART II&mdash;NATURE OF THE CASE</TI>
<P>2. This appeal stems from an action brought by the plaintiffs against the defendants arising out of an Asset Purchase Agreement whereby the corporate plaintiff sold certain assets and assigned contracts to the numbered company defendant.</P>
<P>3. The Statement of Claim was amended to, inter alia, include allegations of negligent and fraudulent misrepresentation, conversion and deceit as against the individual defendants who, at all material times, were the directing minds of 2487048 Ontario Limited (hereinafter referred to as &ldquo;248&rdquo;).</P>
<P>4. The plaintiffs brought a motion for summary judgment against all defendants which was heard by the Honourable Justice Boswell on November 2<SUP>nd</SUP>, 2017. His Honour's decision was reserved.</P>
<P>5. His Honour delivered his reasons on November 27<SUP>th</SUP>, 2017 and granted judgment against 248 in the amount of $85,637.97. However, notwithstanding the fact that all the issues including the allegations of negligent and fraudulent misrepresentation, conversion and deceit were argued, Justice Boswell was not prepared to deal with the claim for personal judgement against Mike Allen and Clark Kent (hereinafter referred to as &ldquo;Allen and Kent&rdquo;) as, because of an apparent mix-up in the file which had been put before him, he was not aware of the Amended Statement of Claim. Justice Boswell's reasons were silent with regard to Orion Fitness Inc.</P>
<P>6. In broad terms Justice Boswell's decision against 248 was based on findings that:
<P1>a) 248 was obliged to assume two loans under the Asset Purchase Agreement including one attributable to leasehold improvements and one attributable to equipment; and</P1>
<P1>b) 248 was liable for damages consisting of amounts the plaintiffs were obliged to pay the Landlord which were triggered by 248's failure to make payments which His Honour found should have been made.</P1></P>
<P>7. Counsel agreed that His Honour should be made aware of the true state of the pleadings and advised him, by letter, accordingly.</P>
<P>8. Very brief supplementary submissions were made on March 6<SUP>th</SUP>, 2018. His Honour reserved judgment. Supplementary reasons were delivered on March 7<SUP>th</SUP>, 2018 granting judgement against the individual defendants. Once again, these reasons were silent as to Orion Fitness Inc.</P>
<P>9. An order was obtained on consent, in this Court, on May 10<SUP>th</SUP>, 2018 extending the time for service of the Notice of Appeal from Justice Boswell's first decision and granting leave for the delivery of an amended notice of appeal. To all intents and purposes, therefore, this would be an appeal from one order but for the mix-up regarding the state of the pleadings.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="III">PART III&mdash;THE FACTS</TI>
<P>10. The plaintiff, 1802248 Ontario Ltd. (hereinafter referred to as &ldquo;180&rdquo;) is a corporation duly incorporated pursuant to the laws of Ontario, which carried on business as an &ldquo;Anytime Fitness&rdquo; franchise in Bradford, Ontario.
<P1><BOLD>Affidavit of Tatiana Johnson Sworn September 6<SUP>th</SUP>, 2016 (hereinafter referred to as &ldquo;Johnson Affidavit&rdquo;) paragraph 2, Appeal Book and Compendium of the Appellants Tab 10, paragraph 2.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>11. The defendant 248 is a corporation incorporated pursuant to the laws of Ontario.</P>
<P>12. On or about October 31<SUP>st</SUP>, 2015 180 and the Johnsons (as sellers) and 248 (as buyer) entered into an Asset Purchase Agreement.
<P1><BOLD>Johnson Affidavit paragraphs 5 and 6, Appeal Book and Compendium of the Appellants Tab 10, paragraphs 5 and 6.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>13. Closing was scheduled for November 1<SUP>st</SUP>, 2015. On that date 248 assumed operation of Anytime Fitness.</P>
<P>14. Allen and Kent were not parties to the Asset Purchase Agreement or the Assignment and Assumption Agreement or Consent to Assignment of Lease referred to in the pleadings.</P>
<P>15. Allen and Kent, on behalf of 248, were concerned that the loans and leases being assumed were attributable to the business which they were purchasing and, specifically, that the loans were with respect to &ldquo;certain equipment being assumed&rdquo;.
<P1><BOLD>Affidavit of Clark Kent sworn October 14<SUP>th</SUP>, 2016 (hereinafter referred to as &ldquo;Kent Affidavit&rdquo;) paragraph 7, Appeal Book and Compendium of the Appellants Tab 12, paragraph 7.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>16. Allen and Kent, on behalf of 248, consistently took the position that they were prepared to pay any amounts properly owing but only after the plaintiffs provided proof that the loans which the plaintiffs wanted to be paid were in conformity with the Asset Purchase Agreement. This did not happen until after the commencement of the action.
<P1><BOLD>Kent Affidavit paragraph 12, Appeal Book and Compendium of the Appellants Tab 12, paragraph 12.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>17. It is important to be borne in mind that the structure of the transaction was negotiated and finalized without involvement of lawyers.
<P1><BOLD>Kent Affidavit paragraph 5, Appeal Book and Compendium of the Appellants Tab 12, paragraph 5.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>18. Eventually, and only months after the commencement of the action, the plaintiffs provided loan documentation with regard to the loans sought to be paid. This disclosed that there were originally two loans totalling $182,526.81. $91,800.00 of that loan facility was attributable to leasehold improvements and $90,726.81 was attributable to equipment. Of the approximate $58,000.00 referred to in the Asset Purchase Agreement, only $18,582.87 was attributable to equipment. The balance was attributable to leasehold improvements.
<P1><BOLD>Johnson Affidavit paragraph 4, Appeal Book and Compendium of the Appellants Tab 10, paragraph 4.</BOLD></P1></P>
<BLOCK3><TI>LEASE DEFAULT</TI>
<P>19. It was agreed to by the parties that 180 would remit payment to the Landlord for the months of November and December and the defendants would pay for rent for the month of January.</P>
<P>20. The arrangements between 180 and 248 contemplated a Statement of Adjustments being prepared. What purported to be a Statement of Adjustments was prepared by the plaintiffs and provided to 248. This document purported to show that 248 owed the plaintiffs $14,941.04.</P>
<P><BOLD>Johnson Affidavit paragraphs 15 through 18 inclusive, Appeal Book and Compendium of the Appellants Tab 10, paragraphs 15 through 18 inclusive.</BOLD></P>
<P>21. Clark Kent did not agree with the Statement of Adjustments. He had no idea what a Statement of Adjustments was. He told Tatiana Johnson that he wanted to review the document with his lawyer. He provided her with a post-dated cheque but advised her it should not be used until he reviewed it with his lawyer. He was advised that the adjustments were not justified under the agreement. Therefore the cheque was dishonoured.
<P1><BOLD>Kent Affidavit paragraph 13, Appeal Book and Compendium of the Appellants Tab 12, paragraph 13.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>22. 248 was not prepared to pay any amounts to the plaintiffs unless and until it was provided reasonable proof that the loans were in conformity with the Asset Purchase Agreement, i.e. that they related to equipment loans and had been used for the purposes of the business.
<P1><BOLD>Kent Affidavit paragraph 12, Appeal Book and Compendium of the Appellants Tab 12, paragraph 12.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>23. It is the position of the plaintiffs that because 248 stopped payment on the cheque referred to in paragraph 20, they defaulted on their obligations to the Landlord pursuant the Assignment Agreement thus triggering obligations pursuant to a deferment agreement.
<P1><BOLD>Johnson Affidavit paragraphs 28 and 29, Appeal Book and Compendium of the Appellants Tab 10, paragraphs 28 and 29.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>24. It is the position of the defendants that 248 was not in default of their obligations under the Asset Purchase Agreement or with regard to the &ldquo;Statement of Adjustments&rdquo; as, at all material times, proof had not been provided that the loans to be assumed were equipment loans.</P>
<P>25. In any event, there is no evidence that any of the defendants was aware of the financial position of the plaintiffs or that the plaintiffs would not be in a position to meet their obligation to the Landlord without monies from the defendants.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI>PERSONAL LIABILITY OF ALLEN AND KENT</TI>
<P>26. Allen and Kent were not parties to the Asset Purchase Agreement or the Assignment and Assumption Agreement and Consent to Assignment of Lease.
<P1><BOLD>Kent Affidavit paragraphs 2 and 4, Appeal Book and Compendium of the Appellants Tab 12, paragraphs 2 and 4.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>27. Allen and Kent are the directing minds of 248. There is no evidence that any of the defendants converted any property of the plaintiffs.</P>
<P>28. There is no evidence that either Allen or Kent made any negligent or fraudulent misrepresentations to the plaintiffs.</P>
<P>29. There is no evidence of any deceit on the part of Allen and Kent.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="IV">PART IV&mdash;ISSUES AND ARGUMENT</TI>
<BLOCK3><TI>SUMMARY JUDGMENT</TI>
<P>30. Rule 20.04(2) of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM> states:
<QUOTE><P><EM>The court shall grant summary judgment if</EM>,</P>
<P><EM>(a) the court is satisfied that there is no genuine issue requiring a trial with respect to a claim or defence; or</EM></P>
<P><EM>(b) the parties agree to have all or part of the claim determined by a summary judgment and the court is satisfied that it is appropriate to grant summary judgment</EM>.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD><EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>, R.R.O. 1990, R.E.G 194</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>31. The leading case with regard to the test for summary judgment is <CASEREF><SOC>Hryniak v. Mauldin</SOC></CASEREF>. If the summary judgment process:
<P1>(a) allows the court to make the necessary findings of fact</P1>
<P1>(b) allows the court to apply the law to the facts and</P1>
<P1>(c) is a proportionate, more expeditious and less expensive means to achieve a just result</P1>
there will be no genuine issue requiring a trial.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Hryniak v. Mauldin</SOC><CITE>2014 S.C.C. 7</CITE><PARANUM>49</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>32. It is conceded that this was an appropriate case for a motion for summary judgment. However, shortly put, it is the Appellants' position that the learned motion's court judge erred in the findings he made.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI>WHAT AMOUNT, IF ANY, IS OWING UNDER THE ASSET PURCHASE AGREEMENT?</TI>
<P>33. It is submitted that the wording of the Asset Purchase Agreement, with regard to the loans/leases to be assumed was clear, unambiguous and not in need of any interpretive process.</P>
<P>34. Surrounding circumstances may be considered in interpreting a contract if the wording is unclear, ambiguous or need of interpretation. However, the circumstances must never be allowed to overwhelm the words of the agreement or to deviate from the text so as to effectively create a new agreement.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Sattva Capital Corp v. Creston Moly Corp</SOC><CITE>[2014] 2 SCR 633</CITE><PARANUM>57</PARANUM></CASEREF> <BOLD>[Sattva].</BOLD></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Glaswegian Enterprises Inc. v. B.C. Tel Mobility Cellular Inc.</SOC><YEAR>1997</YEAR><CITE>101 B. C.A.C. 62</CITE></CASEREF>.</P1></P>
<P>35. The Asset Purchase Agreement is perfectly clear. The purchasers were to assume loans or leases with regard to certain equipment not with regard to leasehold improvements.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Veentis Inc. et al. v. Sunrise Senior Living Real Estate Investment Trust et al</SOC><YEAR>2007</YEAR><CITE>85 O.R. (3d) 254</CITE></CASEREF>.</P1></P>
<P>36. In is reasons, the learned motions court judge referenced the Veentis Inc case.</P>
<P>37. While it is now clear that $18,582.87 was attributable to the equipment lease, this was not known to 248 until after the commencement of this action,. Therefore, at most, 248 would be indebted to the plaintiffs in the amount of $18,582.87 which is within the jurisdiction of the Small Claims Court.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI>248'S LIABILITY PURSUANT TO THE ASSIGNMENT AGREEMENT</TI>
<P>38. It is the plaintiffs' position that 248 was in breach of the Asset Purchase Agreement and that 248's failure to pay amounts owing under the Asset Purchase Agreement caused the plaintiffs to be unable to pay rent to the Landlord thereby triggering additional rent payable under the deferment agreement.</P>
<P>39. Assuming that 248 was in default, which fact is not admitted for the reasons set out above, it is submitted that the amounts paid by the plaintiffs to the Landlord are not recoverable for the simple reason that they were not foreseeable.</P>
<P>40. The classic principles, verging on trite law, are set out in <CASEREF><SOC>Hadley v. Baxendale</SOC></CASEREF>. The learned motions court judge cited <CASEREF><SOC>Hadley v. Baxendale</SOC></CASEREF>. However, it is submitted that the erred insofar as the payment of the deferred rent neither arose naturally, according to the usual course of things, or would have been in the contemplation of both parties at the time they made the contract. Therefore, it is submitted that the claim for this head of damages must fail.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Hadley v. Baxendale</SOC><CITE>(1854) 9 Exch 341</CITE></CASEREF>.</P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI>DO THE PERSONAL DEFENDANTS HAVE LIABILITY FOR ANY PART OF THE PLAINTIFFS' CLAIM?</TI>
<P>41. The starting point for an analysis of this issue is the proposition that a corporation has its own separate identity and the corporate veil protects the officers, directors and shareholders of the corporation from liability for the actions of the corporation.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Salomon v. Salomon &amp; Co Ltd.</SOC><CITE>[1897] A.C. 22</CITE><COURTJUR>H.L.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>.</P1></P>
<P>42. The case against individual defendants is based on allegations of negligent and fraudulent misrepresentation, conversion and deceit. The cases in which the corporate veil has been breached, some of which are referred to by the learned motions court judge involve findings of fraud or the exercise of control for fraudulent or improper purposes.
<P1><BOLD><EM>642947 Ontario Ltd. Fleischer</EM>, 2001 CarswellOnt 4296, [2001] O.J. No. 4771.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Terra Farm Ltd. v. Stud Farm Inc.</SOC><CITE>2010 ONCA 422</CITE></CASEREF>.</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Transamerica Life Insurance Co. of Canada v. Canada Life Assurance Co.</SOC><YEAR>1996</YEAR><CITE>28 O.R. (3d) 324</CITE><COURTJUR>Ont. Gen. Div.</COURTJUR></CASEREF><BOLD>, at 433-434, affirmed [1997] O.J. No. 3754 (Ont. C.A.).</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>43. It is submitted that in the case at bar, there is simply no evidence of Allen or Kent doing anything which could be reasonably construed or interpreted as fraudulent conduct. There is certainly no evidence of misrepresentations whether negligent or fraudulent on the part of Allen or Kent.</P>
<P>44. It is submitted that the Bhasin case while recognizing a principle good faith in informing contractual performance does not extend to the piercing the corporate veil in a case such as this. In any event the evidence in the case at bar does not support a finding that either Allen or Kent lied or knowingly misled any of the plaintiffs.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Bhasin v. Hrynew</SOC><CITE>2014 SCC 71</CITE></CASEREF>.</P1></P>
<P>45. At its highest this is a case in which the corporate defendant, 248, did not pay pursuant to a contract. Every day of the week banks extend credit to corporations and require personal guarantees from the principals of the corporate borrower. It is submitted that if liability is imposed on Allen and Kent on the facts of this case, there will be no need for such personal guarantees in future.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="V">PART VI&mdash;ORDER SOUGHT</TI>
<P>46. The Appellants seek an order allowing the appeal, setting aside the orders of Justice Boswell dated November 27<SUP>th</SUP>, 2017 and March 7<SUP>th</SUP>, 2018 and substituting an order dismissing the action with costs of the appeal and below against 248 and Allen and Kent.</P>
<P>47. In the alternative, the Appellants seek an order dismissing the action, allowing the appeal, setting aside the order of Justice Boswell, dismissing the action as against Allen and Kent and substituting a judgment in the amount of $18,582.87 with costs payable by the plaintiffs here and below.</P>
<P>48. In the further alternative, the Appellants submit that if judgment is entered in the amount of $18,582.87 against 248 costs payable by 248 should be on the Small Claim Court scale and costs otherwise payable by the plaintiffs to Allen and Kent herein below.</P>
<P><BOLD>ALL OF WHICH IS RESPECTFULLY SUBMITTED</BOLD> this 12<SUP>th</SUP> day of June, 2018.</P>
